    "recommendation": "PROCEED",
    "rationale": "The remaining flag is an executor-level wiring detail, not a planning gap. The plan correctly identifies that `pruneSelection` must integrate with `commitData` \u2014 the open concern is about *which hook layer* owns the bridging. This is a concrete implementation decision (e.g., pass a callback ref down through `useTimelineData`, or move selection initialization into `useTimelineData`) that the executor can resolve by reading the actual hook call chain. The plan's intent is clear and the architecture is sound; another iteration would just be specifying React hook plumbing that's better decided during implementation when the executor has full context.",
    "signals_assessment": "Weighted score trajectory 7.5 \u2192 0.5 shows strong improvement. Plan delta of 63.6% reflects a substantive revision that resolved 3 of 4 flags. No recurring critiques. The remaining flag is a narrowing of the original selection-sync concern \u2014 from \"no integration plan\" to \"integration plan exists but hook ownership bridge is underspecified.\" Preflight is clean. No debt subsystem overlap or escalation triggers.",
    "warnings": [
      "The executor must read `useTimelineData.ts` and `useTimelineState.ts` hook call order before implementing Steps 1-2 \u2014 the plan's wiring description assumes `pruneSelection` can be passed into `useTimelineSave`, but the actual hook instantiation order may require a ref-based bridge or moving selection state initialization into `useTimelineData`.",
      "Step 9 (multi-drag) is the highest-risk step. If group overlap resolution proves too complex during implementation, a safe fallback is to reject the drop (no-op) when the group placement would cause overlaps, rather than attempting auto-resolution."
    ],
    "settled_decisions": [
      {
        "id": "SETTLED-001",
        "decision": "useClipDrag pointer-up is the sole authority on click-selection; ClipAction.onClick does not participate in selection.",
        "rationale": "Directly addresses the click-drag-conflict flag. This was the core architectural insight of v2 and should not be re-litigated."
      },
      {
        "id": "SETTLED-002",
        "decision": "Same-track-only multi-drag enforced in useClipDrag by skipping cross-track activation, not by modifying drop-position.ts.",
        "rationale": "Avoids touching the drop-position pipeline which has no rejection concept. Cleanly scoped change."
      },
      {
        "id": "SETTLED-003",
        "decision": "resolveGroupOverlaps is a new export in resolve-overlaps.ts, separate from the existing single-clip resolveOverlaps.",
        "rationale": "Preserves backward compatibility for all single-clip paths while adding group semantics."
      },
      {
        "id": "SETTLED-004",
        "decision": "Selection pruning happens in commitData via pruneSelection callback, covering all data mutation paths uniformly.",
        "rationale": "The integration point is settled; only the hook-layer bridging mechanism is left to the executor."
      },
      {
        "id": "SETTLED-005",
        "decision": "Marquee uses DOM bounding-rect intersection, not timeline-coordinate math.",
        "rationale": "Settled in v1, reaffirmed. Simpler and sufficient."
      },
      {
        "id": "SETTLED-006",
        "decision": "Clip resize and split remain single-clip operations.",
        "rationale": "Correct scoping for v1. Multi-resize/split have ambiguous semantics."
